1. Nf3 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Ng5 Nf6 {Not a good move} 4. Nc3 {Allowing Black to get 
away with it. As we saw from the previous game, better is} (4. Bc4) Bf5 5. Qe2 
{The queen comes to e2 preparing the recapture of the pawn and a pin on the 
e-file} c6 6. Ngxe4 Nbd7 $4 {A classic Caro-Kann type of blunder.} 7. Nd6# 1-0

[Event "Taming the Tennison Gambit"]
[Site "History and White Traps"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Keres"]
[Black "Feltweber, 1933"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "01 History and White Traps"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "taming-the-tennison-gambit/course/21779, variation/2879834"]

1. Nf3 {I've made this line learnable so you can memorize this fun 
correspondence game by Keres by heart.} d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Ng5 Bf5 {A good defense 
and our main repertoire move.} 4. Nc3 {A decent move. As we will see, more 
interesting is} (4. g4 $5) Nf6 {Correct play} 5. Bc4 {Probably best} e6 {So far 
so good} 6. f3 $5 {Keres gambits another pawn} exf3 $1 {Black can take it. 
Another possibility is} ({6...Bc5}) 7. Qxf3 {[%cal Rf3f7,Rg5f7,Rf3b7] Hitting f7 
and b7} c6 $4 {This is the definitive mistake that costs the game. All Black 
needed to do was to play} (7... Bg6) {, after which he's better. Even} (7... 
Nc6) {works.} 8. Nxf7 $1 {Here we go!} Kxf7 {[%cal Bc4f7,Rf3f5] The e-pawn is 
pinned and Bf5 is therefore attacked by the Queen.} 9. Qxf5 Qe7 10. Ne4 h6 11. 
Nc5 {[%cal Rc5e6] Ganging up on e6} g6 12. Qxe6+ Ke8 13. O-O {White's winning. 
The finish is nice} b5 14. Qc8+ Qd8 15. Re1+ Be7 16. Rxe7+ Kxe7 17. Qe6+ Kf8 18. 
Qf7# 1-0

