1. e4 d5 2. Nf3 dxe4 3. Ng5 Bf5 4. Nc3 {Best move} Nf6 5. Qe2 Nc6 $1 6. Qc4 
{[%cal Rc4f7,Rg5f7] A very simplistic attack on f7} e6 7. Ngxe4 {Taking the pawn 
back} Nd4 {The computer likes Nb4 better, but the idea is the same} 8. Qa4+ c6 
9. Bd3 {The knight was attacked twice} a5 {Here I see that I can get his Queen 
in trouble if I take away the a6 square. Perhaps even better was taking on e4 
first and then playing a5} 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Bxf5 exf5 $2 {Somehow I missed the 
fact that b5 here would still trap the Queen...However exf5 is also ok.} (11... 
b5) {and it's all over} 12. Ne2 {Making room for the Queen, but at the expense 
of the king} Nxe2 13. Kxe2 b5 14. Qb3 Bd6 {Aiming to complete development and 
then get the e-file} 15. Re1 O-O 16. g3 Rae8+ 17. Kf1 Rxe1+ 18. Kxe1 Re8+ 19. 
Kf1 f4 20. Kg2 {The final blunder} fxg3 21. hxg3 Re1 {A multi-purpose move, 
making it difficult for him to complete development, but mainly aiming for 
Qh6-h1#} 22. Qf3 $2 Qh6 0-1

