1. e4 d5 2. Nf3 dxe4 3. Ng5 Bf5 4. g4 $5 {An interesting try to make it messy.} 
Bg6 5. Bg2 h5 $1 {The most direct approach! Most White sources only mention} 
(5... Nf6) {Bauer gives} (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 h5 7. Ngxe4 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 hxg4 9. Qxg4 
Nc6 10. d3 Nd4 11. Qd1 Bh5) {after which Black is also better.} 6. gxh5 $4 {A 
blunder} Bxh5 7. f3 e6 $19 {Stockfish considers this to be around -3,75. In some 
lines White's knight is a goner...} 8. Nxe4 Qh4+ 9. Kf1 {If White wants to keep 
the knight then he's just worse in other ways} (9. Ng3 Nc6 10. d3 Nf6) {and 
Black is in the driver's seat with Bc5 and O-O-O to follow (Stockfish: -3,6)} 
Qxe4 10. fxe4 Bxd1 {Black is a piece up and White has no compensation.} *

